---
The Cistern Ring was the oldest known hydraulic regulation system in the world, built by the
Keepers of Measure at the Great Oasis during the early road network era. It comprised four
underground catchment chambers arranged in a ring below the oasis basin: the North Cistern,
shallowest, for daily distribution; the East Cistern, deepest, reserved for drought emergency;
the South Cistern, allocated to caravan provisioning; and the West Cistern, allocated to
agricultural irrigation of the oasis gardens. The ring was not designed to store water—the
natural springs provided that—but to regulate flow. During flood season, excess water was
diverted into the chambers to prevent basin overflow and road erosion. During drought, stored
water was released through calibrated sluice gates to maintain minimum basin levels. Each
chamber had its own sluice master; the four sluice masters together formed the Water Court,
the earliest governing body at the oasis, predating any royal authority by several generations.
The Cistern Ring became the template for every subsequent cistern built along the eastern road
network. Its construction methods, chamber geometry, and sluice calibration standards were
copied by Keeper engineers across the desert corridor.

