Midgaard's institutional relationship to the Cistern Ring is archival: the Measuring House
records that documented the Ring's original construction, calibration standards, and sluice
schedules are the source documents for the Charter of Passage—the legal formula asserting any
traveler reaching the oasis by recognized route has the right to draw water in the amount
specified by caravan charter. Midgaard's charter office treats the Charter of Passage as
foundational caravan law, predating all civic charter systems and carrying precedent weight
accordingly. The Cistern Ring's four-chamber governance model—distributed control with no
single office holding majority authority—appears as an explicit design precedent in early
Midgaard administrative theory. The Continuity faction's defense of distributed institutional
authority traces partly to this precedent. The Ring's collapse in the Battle of the Dry Basin,
when three-power governance fractured into three-way armed conflict, is cited by the Reckoning
faction as proof that distributed authority requires accountability mechanisms between offices
to avoid collapse into competing claims.

