Kiess's legal interest in the Cistern Ring is the Charter of Passage: the inscribed legal
formula on the waystone circle asserting that water access at the oasis cannot be denied to
any traveler arriving by recognized route, regardless of which authority controls the cisterns.
This is the oldest documented example of a travel right that supersedes the governing authority
at a waypoint—the principle Kiess's founding charter generalizes to anti-sealed-warrant doctrine.
No authority at a transit point can deny access to travelers meeting the route-entry standard,
regardless of sealed classifications from upstream jurisdictions. Kiess's Syndic Council has
formally cited the Charter of Passage in two anti-sealed-warrant proceedings as the oldest
precedent for this principle. The Ring's collapse did not extinguish the Charter—the waystone
inscriptions survived the Battle of the Dry Basin intact, and Kiess's position is that surviving
physical inscription constitutes continuous legal force.

