Rakuen's interest in the Cistern Ring is engineering: the root-weave flood-routing architecture
of Rakuen's lower terraces draws on principles documented in Keeper-era cistern engineering,
specifically the use of distributed catchment to redirect excess water away from structures
rather than storing it under pressure. Rakuen's builders adapted the Ring's flood-season
diversion logic to vegetative infrastructure—root networks rather than stone chambers—because
vegetative systems in Rakuen's forest environment are self-repairing in ways stone cisterns
are not. The Jade Magistracy delegation that studied Rakuen's lower terraces during the last
Ledger Vigil identified the Keeper cistern lineage in Rakuen's flood architecture and documented
it in their engineering notes, which they have not shared with Rakuen. Rakuen's Garden Ledger
Clerks have noted this asymmetry formally. The Keeper origin of Rakuen's hydraulic approach
is independently confirmed in the Clerks' archive—they simply want to know what the Kowloon
delegation concluded about its current structural status.

