Mafdet's Ledger Houses recognize the Cistern Ring's Water Court as the earliest documented
model of multi-bloc civic governance structured around functional specialization rather than
territorial control. The four sluice masters held authority over specific operational domains
without any one controlling the others. The Strandline Compact's three-bloc structure—Harbor
Wardens, Ledger Houses, Sand-Sea Carters' Guild—is analogous in form: functional specialization,
distributed veto power, and a shared asset (the harbor) that no single bloc can shut down
without triggering the others' combined opposition. The "harbor first" principle of the Compact
is structurally equivalent to the Charter of Passage for the Cistern Ring: the shared asset's
functioning takes precedence over any bloc's competitive interest. Mafdet's institutional
historians treat the Water Court as the founding precedent for the Compact's governance model,
though the Chain is longer and the Keeper connection is not formally acknowledged in the Compact's
own documentation.

