Deltari Reed Law treats hydraulic systems as witnessed measurement problems: flow rates, sluice
conditions, and water-debt ledgers must all be independently confirmed and regularly re-measured
because conditions change. The Cistern Ring's original calibration standards required quarterly
sluice inspections with co-signature from all four masters—no single master's reading was
accepted as authoritative without at least one independent confirmation. This is the earliest
documented application of Deltari measurement principles to hydraulic governance. Deltari
engineers who have studied the Ring's ruins consistently note that the inspection protocol
was the mechanism that maintained functional accuracy across the four chambers over long periods.
The Ring's collapse came after governance fracture eliminated the co-inspection requirement,
not after physical failure of the engineering itself. The lesson Deltari draw: hydraulic
infrastructure outlasts the measurement protocols that maintain it, and when measurement
protocols collapse, engineering follows within generations.

