Kethari water-memory preserves knowledge of the Cistern Ring from before the Water Court era—
not as institutional history but as ecological observation of the oasis basin itself. Kethari
who have dwelt in the desert corridor for generations carry oral records of the basin's natural
behavior before the Ring was constructed: the flood-season overflow patterns, the drought-season
spring diminishment cycles, the way the basin's edges changed over time. The Ring's engineering
modified these patterns; Kethari water-memory preserved the pre-engineering baseline. When
the Ring's collapse allowed the basin to contract toward its unregulated state, Kethari
observations provided the only existing account of what that state looked like—information
the Spring Wardens who now manage the surviving north cistern chamber have consulted when
projecting long-term basin behavior. Kethari do not evaluate the Cistern Ring as an institution;
they evaluate it as a modification to an aquifer they have known longer than the institution
existed.

