Deltari archivists working with Rakuen's flood architecture team have identified the Cistern
Ring's South Cistern—the chamber allocated to caravan provisioning—as the oldest documented
example of water-debt ledgering: systematic accounting of water drawn against water rights,
with caravan charters serving as the primary debt instruments. Rakuen's own water-debt system,
used to manage flood-season catchment distribution across the terraced districts, follows the
same ledger structure. Deltari Reed Law requires that water-debt ledgers be updated at each
draw, witnessed by an independent recorder, and reconciled against the cistern level at the
end of each market period. The Ring's original caravan provisioning records, fragments of which
survive in the Measuring House ruins, show the same structure—suggesting either direct
transmission through Keeper-era documentation or independent convergence on the same
measurement principles. Deltari prefer the convergence explanation; independent confirmation
of measurement standards strengthens their evidentiary weight.
